6/ In summary, yes, general national productivity is catching up to the US, but that comparison is apples to oranges. US Labor force is 6.62x more productive than Chinas. China competes w US is by working their population (4.2x larger) 1.8x harder, and still comes up 35% short.

5/ Lets assume there are similar rules around lunch/food breaks, but my guess is the lunch breaks are shorter in China, just a hunch.

GDP per hour worked in the US based on the 40 hour work week is $35 an hour.

GDP per hour worked in China is $5.28 an hour

That's 6.62x higher.

4/ But even this doesn't come close to telling the full story. Why? Because we have different labor laws and norms. 

In the US 9am-5pm for 5 days is the norm (40 hour work week).

In China 9am-9pm for 6 days a week is the norm (72 hour work week)
